default2.8     
defaultIn some areas, particularly i
defaultn the north of England
default,
default we have historically allowed under-occupation of three and four bedroom houses
default. This is both because this is the predominant property type and also
default because we 
defaultcannot
default meet
default 
defaultthe large demand for two bedroom homes
default. Additionally, we try 
defaultto
default actively manage levels of child density, thereby allowing families to grow into a property and help with community stability and cohesion. Most local authority allocation schemes allowed for under occupation by one bedroom for the same reasons. Generall
defaulty local authorities have now changed their approach to allocating properties to fall in line with the housing benefit changes which came into effect April 2013 and do not nominate households who would under occupy and be affected by the benefit changes.
default&#xa0;
defaultCo
defaultnsequently, 
defaultdemand is falling for larger homes in some northern towns and cities (examples are Hull, Bradford, Leeds, 
defaultand Newcastle
default-upon-Tyne). In these locations the local authority 
defaultis
default either struggling to nominate suitable housing applicants or have simp
defaultly said they cannot nominate applicants for larger homes for the foreseeable future.
