default3.1
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default 
defaultW
defaulte are currently 
defaultundertaking a piece of research 
defaultassessing the likely level of savings to Government
default generated by the under-occupation penalty
default. We are working with three
default other social landlords -
default&#xa0;
defaultRiverside
default, Gentoo and Wigan and Leigh Housing - with support from the Centre for Housing Policy (University of York). Using the DWP’s own savings impact model, 
defaultand re-r
defaultunning it with data drawn from 
defaultreal experience across the four organisations since April, our initial findings indicate that the level of savings projected by DWP are likely to have been overstated to 
defaulta significant extent
default, 
defaultpossibly by as much as a 
defaultthird. Despite the generation of savings being one of the Government’s key objectives for the policy, and central to Parliamentary debates during the passage of the Welfare Reform Bill, our study confirms the DWP’s own assessment that 
defaultthere is 
default“uncertainty
default about likely claimant and landlord responses to the introduction of the social sector size criteria [which] creates uncertainty about the benefit saving likely to be realised” (DWP 2012 p13). Our work also highlights significant deficiencies in the design
default of the model which are likely to have further overstated the level of savings generated through the implementation of the under-occupation penalty. 
